$ completion-generator
======================

Demonstrates Click's new completion script generator capabilities.

This example shows:
- A command to directly generate completion scripts (bash/zsh/fish)
- Subcommands with nested groups
- Option value hints using Choice type
- Dynamic completion candidates using shell_complete functions

Installation
------------

.. code-block:: bash

    pip install --editable .

Usage
-----

Generate completion scripts:

.. code-block:: bash

    # Generate bash completion script
    compgen completion bash

    # Generate zsh completion script
    compgen completion zsh

    # Generate fish completion script
    compgen completion fish

    # List available shells
    compgen completion --list

    # Show installation instructions
    compgen completion bash --install

Enable Completion
-----------------

For Bash:

.. code-block:: bash

    eval "$(compgen completion bash)"

Or save to a file:

.. code-block:: bash

    compgen completion bash > ~/.compgen-complete.bash
    echo ". ~/.compgen-complete.bash" >> ~/.bashrc

For Zsh:

.. code-block:: zsh

    eval "$(compgen completion zsh)"

For Fish:

.. code-block:: fish

    compgen completion fish > ~/.config/fish/completions/compgen.fish

Test the Completion
-------------------

After enabling completion, try:

.. code-block:: bash

    # Subcommand completion
    compgen <TAB><TAB>
    compgen use<TAB>

    # Nested subcommands
    compgen user <TAB><TAB>
    compgen user a<TAB>

    # Option completion
    compgen read -<TAB><TAB>
    compgen read --out<TAB>

    # Choice value hints
    compgen read --output <TAB><TAB>      # json, yaml, xml, csv
    compgen read --mode <TAB><TAB>        # read, write, append

    # Dynamic candidates
    compgen env <TAB><TAB>                 # Environment variables
    compgen user add <TAB><TAB>            # Users with descriptions

Programmatic API
----------------

You can also use the API directly in Python:

.. code-block:: python

    import click
    from click import generate_completion_script, list_available_shells

    @click.group()
    def mycli():
        pass

    # List available shells
    print(list_available_shells())  # ['bash', 'zsh', 'fish']

    # Generate completion script
    bash_script = generate_completion_script(mycli, "bash", "mycli")
    print(bash_script)

    zsh_script = generate_completion_script(mycli, "zsh", "mycli")
    print(zsh_script)

    fish_script = generate_completion_script(mycli, "fish", "mycli")
    print(fish_script)
